  "text": "Diagnosis of diabetes may also be improved using sensors that can detect a concentration gradient. One of the symptoms of diabetes is the increase in acetone in the patient's breath. In an attempt to develop a noninvasive method to detect blood glucose levels, Zhang et al. developed a LAPS sensor that detected the concentration gradient of acetone from a patient's breath [CITATION_1] . With improvements in repeatability and selectivity (or detecting another analyte that is also tied to diabetes), this type of sensor could provide a method to diagnose diabetes or measure blood glucose levels noninvasively.",
